Setting up AWS account
Introduction
Imagine you’re working on a new project, a web app that you hope will eventually reach thousands, maybe even millions, of users. But here’s the challenge: if you had to buy and set up physical servers every time you wanted to test or launch something, it’d be pretty costly, not to mention a huge time sink. That’s where a cloud platform like Amazon Web Services (AWS) comes into play. 

AWS provides all the resources you need right at your fingertips. So, instead of worrying about racks of servers, you can focus on building your app, knowing that as it grows, AWS can grow with it seamlessly and on-demand.

In this reading, you’ll learn how to set up your own AWS account, an essential step for deploying and managing applications in the cloud. You’ll explore the registration process, how to configure billing settings, and examine the AWS Free Tier.

Overview of AWS
AWS is like an all-in-one toolbox for developers. It’s a platform that provides various services, from storage to virtual servers to databases and more, all available in the cloud. Think of it as your on-demand, pay-as-you-go setup for practically any computing need. Instead of investing in costly physical servers and spending hours on setup, AWS gives you a ready-made infrastructure that’s scalable, reliable, and flexible. You just tap into the resources you need precisely when you need them.

You might be wondering, why do I need my own AWS account? 

Well, it’s all about flexibility and control. With an AWS account, you can deploy apps, store data, handle databases, run analytics, and so much more, all with just a few clicks. The best part is that AWS scales with you. Whether you’re just experimenting with a small app or ready to launch something bigger, AWS adjusts to your needs.

Now that you understand why setting up an AWS account is beneficial, let’s dive into the process. Creating an account is the starting point for providing access to AWS services and resources. Follow these steps to set up your account.

Step 1: Register for an AWS account
Start by navigating to the AWS registration page at 
aws.amazon.com
. Click the Create an AWS Account button.

The AWS registration page.
Step 2: Enter your account information
In the Root user email address field, enter your email address, enter an AWS account name, and click Verify email address. AWS will then email a verification code to this address.

Enter and confirm your Root user password and click Continue.

The Sign up for AWS page.
