Step 3: Add your contact information
After clicking Create an AWS Account, you can choose a Personal or Business account. As this setup is for an individual, select Personal.

The Sign up for AWS page displaying the Contact information section.
Read the AWS Customer Agreement, then check the box to accept, and click Continue. AWS sends a confirmation email to the address you registered.

Step 4: Set up billing 
Here, you’ll need to enter your payment information. AWS requires this to activate your account, even if you plan to use the Free Tier. The Free Tier has certain usage limits at no cost, so you can experiment without being charged if you stay within these limits.

The Sign up for AWS page displaying the Billing information section.
Step 5: Verify your contact number
AWS asks for a mobile number to verify your identity. Choose your country code, enter a mobile number to receive a code immediately, and complete the CAPTCHA if prompted. You’ll receive an automated call or text shortly after with a PIN. Enter the PIN to verify, then click Continue.

The Phone verification page.
Step 6: Choose your support plan
For now, select the Basic Support (Free Tier) plan. This plan is sufficient for starting and learning.

The Support Plan page displaying the highlighted Basic Support plan.
Step 7: Complete sign up
Once you pick a support plan, you’ll see a confirmation page letting you know your account is being activated. This usually only takes a few minutes, but in some cases, it can take up to 24 hours.

Configure billing settings 
Once registered, you’ll be directed to the AWS Management Console. The dashboard is where you can manage your resources and services. Before diving into services, let’s check out a couple of essential settings:

The AWS Management Console displaying the Dashboard.
Access the billing dashboard
From the top navigation bar, select your account name, then Billing Dashboard. Here, you can track your spending, set up alerts, and view usage statistics.

The Billing Dashboard displaying the Billing and Cost Management Home page.
Set up budget alerts
Setting up budget alerts is essential to avoid unexpected charges. Navigate to Budgets in the billing dashboard and create a budget to receive notifications if you exceed Free Tier limits or hit a specific spending amount. This simple step can help you stay in control of your costs.

The Billing dashboard displaying the AWS Budgets page.
Understand AWS Free Tier
The AWS Free Tier lets you explore and try out AWS services at no cost, up to specific usage limits for each service. It includes three free offers: 12 Months Free, Always Free, and Short-Term Free Trials.

The AWS Free Tier flowchart illustrating the three free offers.
12 Months Free: Certain services, like 750 hours of EC2 usage per month, are free for your first 12 months from the date you activate your account.

Always Free: Some services stay free up to specific limits as long as you’re an AWS customer.

Short-Term Free Trials: A few services are free for a limited time or up to a one-time usage limit.

The Free Tier web page displaying the types of offers available.
Check the Free Tier page for full details on what’s covered. If you exceed these limits, you’ll pay regular, pay-as-you-go rates for the additional usage.

Manage user access: Root User vs. IAM Users
After setting up billing preferences and understanding the AWS Free Tier, the next step is managing access and security. AWS accounts have different user types, each with specific roles and permissions. 

Let’s explore the two main types you’ll encounter: the Root User and IAM Users.

The User types illustrated in a flow chart.
Root User
The Root User is like the primary administrator for your AWS account, with full, unrestricted access to everything. This user can manage and modify all settings across the account, including billing and payment information. Only the Root User has permission to delete the AWS account entirely, making it a powerful role.

The Root User privileges illustrated in a flow chart.
Only the Root User can access a few security-specific settings, like setting up account-wide Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA). Finally, only the Root User has the authority to create and manage IAM users and roles, which lets you assign specific permissions to others working within the account. In short, the Root User has the keys to everything in AWS, so it’s best to use this account sparingly and keep it secure.

IAM Users
IAM (Identity and Access Management) Users are the everyday users within your AWS account, with access tailored to specific tasks or roles. Unlike the Root User, IAM Users have controlled permissions to decide exactly what they can and can’t do.  For example, one IAM User might only need permission to manage EC2 instances, while another might need access to an S3 bucket.

IAM (Identity and Access Management) Users privileges illustrated in a flow chart.
IAM Users cannot access billing or high-level account settings unless you grant it to them. They also can’t delete the account or make significant changes, which keeps things secure. You can customize IAM roles for different job functions, making it easy to manage access as your team or projects grow. Plus, you can add MFA for extra security on each IAM account.

In short, IAM Users give you flexible, safe ways to delegate access without giving away the master keys of the Root User.

Conclusion
With your AWS account set up, you can access a vast ecosystem of cloud services that can power everything from small projects to enterprise-level applications. Setting up an account and configuring billing might seem simple, but this groundwork is essential for managing your AWS resources effectively. Next, you’ll explore specific services within AWS, diving into EC2 instances where you can launch virtual servers on demand. Great job getting through this initial setup!


  

